00:19 SW starts talking
9:15 Do you think you in the future people will look at our societal interest in maths science the same way we view alchemist and theologians of old?
18:45 Tell us about the history of chess computers and approaches they used before deep learning.
27:04 Can you talk about the history of software packaging and distribution?
46:52 My brain came online around needing 2 CDs for games and i thought that was a pain.
47:03 I might be misremembering, but I think we put a piece of masking tape on floppy disks to circumvent copy protection.
47:50 Would love your thoughts on internet pseudonymity and its history!
1:11:39 How has the "central hub" of science changed geographically overtime and what may the reasons be for this change?
1:22:59 There is obviously a link between training clergymen (the original role of most western universities) and the growth of early modern science.
1:27:48 Any thoughts on different methods of storing information in terms of resilience over long timescales?
1:32:28 Kuneiform is mostly only preserved because it was stamped in clay tablets. All the really 'good stuff' (science, poetry, etc.) was usually written on biological material like hides and papyrus, and obviously, they didn't age that well.
1:33:28 Dutch East Indian Company records on paper exist till today from 1600 - 1700.
1:34:36 In light of the recent law requiring free access to all federally funded research (and associated data), can you talk about how scientific knowledge and data has been shared throughout history?

